fore the creation of Adam, the cosmos existed as a fashioned, lifeless body without a spirit, resembling an unpolished mirror :لما شاء الحق سبحانه من حيث أسماؤه الحسنى التي لا يبلغها الإحصاء أن يرى أعيانها... أوجد العالم كله وجود شبح مسوّى لا روح فيه، فكان كمرآة غير مجلوّة... فكان آدم عين جلاء تلك المرآة و روح تلك الصورة This may be translated as: "When the Truth, glory be to Him, willed from the aspect of His most beautiful names... to see their essences... He brought the entire world into existence as a fashioned body without a spirit, and it was like an unpolished mirror... thus Adam was the very clarity of that mirror and the spirit of that form." For Ibn ʿArabī, Adam's soul is inherently composite and universal because he is the "comprehensive container" (al-kawn al-jāmiʿ) who encompasses all the divine names and cosmic realities. All human souls are indeed ontological fragments, reflections, or individualizations of this universal Adam, who is the "single soul" (al-nafs al-wāḥidah) referenced in Quran 4:1.This composite nature is directly implied in Quran 2:30-34, where God announces to the angels that He is establishing a khalīfah (vicegerent) on Earth. The angels, recalling the corruption of the pre-human inhabitants, ask: "Will You place therein one who spreads corruption and sheds blood?" God replies: "Indeed, I know that which you do know not," and subsequently teaches Adam "all the names" (al-asmāʾ kullahā). In esoteric commentaries (such as those of al-Kāshānī and Ibn ʿArabī), this means Adam's soul was endowed with the potentiality of all subsequent human souls and all divine attributes, making him the mediator between the Absolute and the created world. The angels, possessing only singular, specialized functions, represent specific cosmic forces (the "faculties" of the universal body), whereas Adam represents the unified, composite whole.Primary Texts Evaluated: Fuṣūṣ al-Ḥikam (Chapter 1) , Tafsir al-Tabari (on Q 2:30), Tafsir al-Razi (Mafātīḥ al-Ghay