h the physical grave, describing a passive "sleep" until judgment day. The primary texts describe it as a highly dynamic, imaginal world where the soul's inner character is instantly externalized into objective forms (either garden-like or fire-like), undergoing an active, conscious experience of reward or punishment.Confidence Level: High.Null Results: The Quran does not explicitly mention the names "Munkar" and "Nakir"; their specific names, appearance, and interrogation protocols are derived from Hadith literature (e.g., Sahiḥ Muslim, Sunan al-Tirmidhī).Q5: Comparative Eschatology: Farsi Chinvat Bridge vs. Quranic BarzakhA comparative structural analysis reveals a profound shift when transitioning from the Zoroastrian eschatological system to the early Islamic model. In Zoroastrian texts (such as the Pahlavi Bundahishn and Wizidagiha-i Zadspram), post-mortem transit is characterized by extreme navigational complexity. The central feature is the Cinvatō Peretu (Chinvat Bridge), a dynamic, sentient checkpoint that actively tests the passing soul:Chinvat-o-Peretu... the souls of the pious alone can pass the bridge while those of the wicked fall from it down into Hell... it will be 9 lances high and 27 arrows wide for the pious, but as sharp and narrow as the edge of the sword for the sinner The soul must navigate this unstable structure, accompanied by its Daēna (the personified reflection of its earthly actions, appearing either as a beautiful maiden or a hideous hag). The bridge is a highly dynamic, active checkpoint requiring navigational balance.When Islam emerged in Late Antiquity, it adapted certain Middle Iranian concepts but structurally rearranged them. The Quranic Barzakh represents a deliberate stripping of this immediate post-mortem navigational complexity. Instead of an active, dangerous crossing immediately after death, the Barzakh is established as a passive, static holding pattern—a cosmic wall (ḥāʾil) that prevents any transit or movement until the 