ames of power (onomata) to physically dissolve the Archons' power and force the gates to open.Primary Texts Evaluated: Coptic: Pistis Sophia (Chapters 32, 131-134) , The First and Second Books of Jeu.What Text Actually Says vs. Modern Summaries: Modern popular summaries often present Gnosticism as a soft, poetic form of early Christian mysticism focusing on internal self-esteem. The primary Coptic manuscripts present an incredibly detailed, highly technical, and almost mechanical system of protective keys, geometric seals, and password-based security clearances required to break through a hostile cosmic blockade.Confidence Level: High.Q9: The Sixth Palace ThresholdIn the Jewish mystical texts of the Hekhalot literature—specifically Hekhalot Rabbati—the visionary’s ascent through the seven heavenly palaces (hekhalot) is fraught with extreme danger. The most notorious threshold is the marble floor test of the Sixth Palace :כשפירשתי מידת עליית וירידת המרכבה... בן עזאי הציץ בהיכל הששי וראה זיו אויר אבני שיש שהיו סלולות בהיכל ולא סבל נופו ופתח פיו ושאלם מים הלلو מה טיבן ומת This translates as: "When I explained the measure of the ascent and descent of the Chariot... Ben Azzai peeked into the Sixth Palace and saw the brilliance of the air of the marble stones that were paved in the Palace, and his body could not endure it, and he opened his mouth and asked them: 'What is the nature of these waters?' and he died." The test is installed by the guardians of the Sixth Palace, led by the archangels Dumiel and Kazfiel. The floor is paved with pure, ultra-clear marble stones that emit a brilliant, undulating sheen resembling flowing water. When the visionary (Yored Merkabah) reaches this threshold, the sight is so visually convincing that the uninitiated or unprepared traveler is tricked into asking: "Water, water! What is the nature of this?".This question is a fatal error. The guardians immediately interpret this misidentification as a sign of spiritual unworthiness and a lack